    "id": "noscope-mpl",
    "title": "Signal handling policy",
    "description": "Provenance REQ: jn764cw67wc4h6d9st0qpe903x83vbgz\n\nThe hard part of the tool. What happens when the parent is killed? Revocation must be best-effort with configurable timeout. SIGKILL cannot be caught so rely on TTL expiry as safety net.\n\nRules:\n- NS-003: Revoke on exit guarantee — attempt revocation on child exit regardless of reason; best-effort with timeout+retry; SIGKILL exception relies on TTL\n- NS-011: TTL as safety net — ultimate revocation guarantee; if SIGKILL/network-down/retries-exhausted, credential still expires at TTL; never mint without TTL\n- NS-014: Revocation must be idempotent — already-revoked/expired treated as success (exit 0)\n- NS-026: Signal forwarding policy — SIGTERM/SIGHUP/SIGINT forwarded to child process group; configurable grace period (default 30s); SIGKILL after grace; then revoke; ignore SIGPIPE\n- NS-027: Revocation timeout and retry budget — configurable wall-clock budget (default 10s); exponential backoff (base 500ms, max 3 retries); budget=0 disables\n- NS-028: Double-signal escalation — second SIGTERM/SIGINT during shutdown: immediately SIGKILL process group, abandon revocation, log, exit; TTL is safety net\n- NS-029: Multi-credential revocation on signal — revoke all active credentials in parallel within budget; one failure must not prevent others\n- NS-066: Minimum TTL enforcement — minimum 60 seconds; prevents misconfiguration and high-frequency token generation\n- NS-067: Maximum TTL enforcement — configurable max (default 12 hours); rejects excessive TTLs; max blast radius for mint mode\n\nProvenance stats: 0 resolutions, 9 rules",
